WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:07.917
♪

00:08.667 --> 00:10.041
(doorbell rings)

00:10.041 --> 00:13.000
-Hi, come on in. Come on in.
COLLEEN: Hi!

00:13.000 --> 00:15.667
JEN: Thank you so much
for watching Lark last minute.

00:15.667 --> 00:17.166
I know, Colleen,
you had to work today.

00:17.166 --> 00:19.583
And, Matt, you had to...

00:19.583 --> 00:20.959
So, thank you.

00:20.959 --> 00:23.083
GREG: Yeah, I mean,
first interview for preschool.

00:23.083 --> 00:24.000
-Oh, wow.
-Oh, hey.

00:24.000 --> 00:27.375
GREG: And they place a lot
of emphasis on diversity so...

00:27.375 --> 00:28.417
(in bad British accent)
I’m gonna have to do

00:28.417 --> 00:30.208
the interview like this.

00:30.208 --> 00:31.291
-I wouldn’t.
-Yeah, what’s that?

00:31.291 --> 00:32.250
COLLEEN: But no worries.

00:32.250 --> 00:34.083
This is like my dream day off.

00:34.083 --> 00:35.166
I love Lark.

00:35.166 --> 00:38.458
Oh, and she is
so crazy about you.

00:38.458 --> 00:39.458
I mean, she can’t stop
talking about you.

00:39.458 --> 00:40.625
-No.
JEN: You know?

00:40.625 --> 00:41.959
But just be sure
when she wakes up

00:41.959 --> 00:43.625
to reintroduce yourself.

00:43.625 --> 00:44.583
-Okay.
-Okay.

00:44.583 --> 00:46.709
And so I left you a schedule

00:46.709 --> 00:48.041
and all of her favorite toys
and books,

00:48.041 --> 00:49.125
some of which are
in our bathroom.

00:49.125 --> 00:51.125
That’s a question for Greg.

00:51.125 --> 00:52.333
-But we should really get...
-Okay.

00:52.333 --> 00:54.375
MATT: Okay, and, uh, you know,
where’s her stroller

00:54.375 --> 00:55.834
in case we want
to take her outside,

00:55.834 --> 00:57.458
a free-range Lark?

00:57.458 --> 00:59.125
-Oh.
-You know what,

00:59.125 --> 01:01.792
I think let’s make today
just, like, an inside day.

01:01.792 --> 01:02.792
GREG: Yeah.
JEN: Yeah, just ’cause

01:02.792 --> 01:04.583
we don’t want to risk her
making friends with a new baby

01:04.583 --> 01:06.000
’cause then we’d have to be
nice to the parents.

01:06.000 --> 01:07.750
-Uh-huh. Got it.
-Right. Yeah.

01:07.750 --> 01:09.125
COLLEEN: Very good.
JEN: Okay.

01:09.125 --> 01:10.583
GREG: Thanks, guys
COLLEEN: Bye, guys. Good luck.

01:10.583 --> 01:12.375
MATT: Take care.

01:12.375 --> 01:14.083
COLLEEN: Aw, this is fun.

01:14.083 --> 01:16.625
It’s like a little window
into our future as parents.

01:16.625 --> 01:17.750
You think
if we ever have a kid,

01:17.750 --> 01:19.125
it’s gonna be this cute?

01:19.125 --> 01:20.583
Even cuter.

01:20.583 --> 01:23.166
Ours is gonna be one
of those multiracial babies

01:23.166 --> 01:24.667
which are the only kinds
they put in commercials

01:24.667 --> 01:26.083
-these days.
-Right.

01:26.083 --> 01:27.166
I’m kind of a baby expert

01:27.166 --> 01:29.458
’cause, you know, I looked
after all of Heather’s kids,

01:29.458 --> 01:32.375
and then we had
this little baby bird that...

01:32.375 --> 01:33.375
didn’t make it.

01:33.375 --> 01:34.458
Well, I’m glad you know
what you’re doing

01:34.458 --> 01:36.583
’cause I didn’t babysit much
growing up.

01:36.583 --> 01:37.875
Really?
Not even in high school?

01:37.875 --> 01:39.750
Well, I did once,
but then I became known

01:39.750 --> 01:41.667
as "the girl who flirted
with a dad,"

01:41.667 --> 01:44.500
and that kind of killed
my career and a marriage.

01:44.500 --> 01:47.917
♪

01:47.917 --> 01:50.250
And that’s why everyone
was very confused

01:50.250 --> 01:52.625
at your mommy
and daddy’s wedding.

01:52.625 --> 01:53.709
I--I don’t get it.

01:53.709 --> 01:55.375
She giggled at this thing
for like ten minutes

01:55.375 --> 01:56.333
and suddenly she hates it.

01:56.333 --> 01:57.291
And now I’m starting
to wonder if it was

01:57.291 --> 01:58.750
ever really all that funny
to begin with.

01:58.750 --> 02:00.959
She’s just staring into space.

02:00.959 --> 02:02.417
-Is that normal?
MATT: I don’t know.

02:02.417 --> 02:04.291
This is a weird baby, man.

02:04.291 --> 02:06.500
Ooh, I know, we could
take her to a pet store,

02:06.500 --> 02:08.166
and let her put her fingers
in all the cages.

02:08.166 --> 02:09.125
MATT: That’s a great idea.

02:09.125 --> 02:10.417
We’re ready for an outing.

02:10.417 --> 02:13.166
Besides, it’ll put some life
into this dumb Greg baby.

02:13.166 --> 02:14.834
COLLEEN: Oh, wait.
Jen said we didn’t need

02:14.834 --> 02:16.875
to take her anywhere
in the stroller.

02:16.875 --> 02:18.834
We’re not gonna take a stroller.

02:18.834 --> 02:20.375
♪

02:20.375 --> 02:21.959
(gasps)

02:21.959 --> 02:24.792
COLLEEN: Okay, I’ve got
a bottle and snacks

02:24.792 --> 02:26.250
and that puppet
in case it makes a comeback.

02:26.250 --> 02:27.375
You really thought
of everything.

02:27.375 --> 02:29.500
Yeah. I think I’m gonna be
a really good mom.

02:29.500 --> 02:30.542
I know you are.

02:30.542 --> 02:32.917
COLLEEN: Aw.

02:32.917 --> 02:35.083
(Velcro ripping, thudding)

02:35.083 --> 02:37.083
♪

02:37.083 --> 02:38.333
MATT: She’s fine.

02:38.333 --> 02:40.500
COLLEEN: Oh, I feel terrible.

02:40.500 --> 02:42.583
Sleeping with that dad
in high school was a sign

02:42.583 --> 02:44.917
I wasn’t meant
to take care of kids.

02:44.917 --> 02:46.208
You said you just
flirted with him.

02:46.208 --> 02:48.125
Huh?

02:48.125 --> 02:49.375
Maybe we should call Jen.

02:49.375 --> 02:51.500
No way. We’ll look incompetent.

02:51.500 --> 02:52.583
And then when we have
kids of our own,

02:52.583 --> 02:54.250
everyone will be worried
that we can’t handle it.

02:54.250 --> 02:55.250
Well, maybe we can’t.

02:55.250 --> 02:57.917
Oh, we dropped one baby
on her face.

02:57.917 --> 02:59.750
We’ll be much more careful
with ours.

02:59.750 --> 03:00.875
Yeah.

03:00.875 --> 03:02.041
-You’re right.
-Yeah.

03:02.041 --> 03:03.041
COLLEEN: I’m glad we can learn
these lessons

03:03.041 --> 03:04.792
-on someone else’s baby.
-Totally.

03:04.792 --> 03:07.291
(crying)

03:07.291 --> 03:09.125
Really? We drop you
on your head, you don’t cry.

03:09.125 --> 03:10.750
Now you’re crying at this?

03:10.750 --> 03:12.875
-Greg baby.
-Oh, no. What do we do?

03:12.875 --> 03:14.041
Oh, no, no, no.
Don’t answer.

03:14.041 --> 03:15.625
No, they’ll hear in our voice
that something is wrong,

03:15.625 --> 03:16.709
and then they’ll start
to worry,

03:16.709 --> 03:18.083
so just, like,
let it ring forever.

03:18.083 --> 03:19.667
-Okay.
-Okay.

03:19.667 --> 03:20.834
(crying)

03:20.834 --> 03:22.542
Hi.

03:22.542 --> 03:24.667
♪

03:24.667 --> 03:27.917
I think it totally works.

03:27.917 --> 03:29.750
I can still see it.

03:29.750 --> 03:32.083
Yeah. Maybe I shouldn’t
have been so quick to dismiss

03:32.083 --> 03:33.333
your Blue Man Group idea.

03:33.333 --> 03:34.792
(whirring, gasps)

03:34.792 --> 03:35.709
COLLEEN: That’s the garage.

03:35.709 --> 03:37.709
-They’re home.
-Okay, whoa, whoa, stay calm.

03:37.709 --> 03:38.625
It’s not a big deal.

03:38.625 --> 03:39.917
Lark is fine.

03:39.917 --> 03:43.542
And maybe we don’t
have to explain anything.

03:43.542 --> 03:45.291
Okay. You go there.
You stay there, okay?

03:47.917 --> 03:49.250
-Hi!
-Hi.

03:49.250 --> 03:50.208
COLLEEN: Oh, no.

03:50.208 --> 03:52.917
No, God, you opened the door
into her face.

03:52.917 --> 03:54.166
I think that’s
gonna leave a mark.

03:54.166 --> 03:55.875
Oh, yep, there it is.

03:55.875 --> 03:58.542
JEN: Yeah. You do know
that we have cameras everywhere

03:58.542 --> 04:00.667
and we watched the whole thing
on my phone?

04:00.667 --> 04:02.208
MATT: No, we did not know that.

04:02.208 --> 04:03.625
JEN: Give me my child.

04:03.625 --> 04:05.917
Oh, sweetie, are you okay?

04:05.917 --> 04:07.166
COLLEEN: We’re really sorry.

04:07.166 --> 04:09.208
-And, look, she’s fine.
-Yeah, and sorry about,

04:09.208 --> 04:10.458
you know,
having sex on your bed.

04:10.458 --> 04:11.375
COLLEEN: Yeah.

04:11.375 --> 04:13.291
GREG: Well, we don’t have
cameras in the bedroom.

04:13.291 --> 04:14.792
-Okay.
-Oh.

04:14.792 --> 04:17.125
Uh, I was gonna say
that I was pretty impressed

04:17.125 --> 04:19.834
with the way you two
came together in a crisis.

04:19.834 --> 04:20.917
The first time
Lark tripped over

04:20.917 --> 04:22.583
one of my shoes
and got a fat lip,

04:22.583 --> 04:24.542
Greg gave me the stink eye
and called me a slut.

04:24.542 --> 04:25.458
COLLEEN: Huh.

04:25.458 --> 04:28.583
She picks up
her shoes now, though.

04:28.583 --> 04:30.041
Look at that. See?

04:30.041 --> 04:31.875
-We do make a good team.
-We do.

04:31.875 --> 04:34.000
Maybe we’re gonna be
great parents after all.

04:34.000 --> 04:35.458
Well, you know,
you did concuss a baby

04:35.458 --> 04:36.750
and then try to fix it
with a makeover,

04:36.750 --> 04:38.291
but I guess
everyone’s definition

04:38.291 --> 04:40.250
of "great" is different.

04:40.250 --> 04:42.625
Well, uh, I’m gonna
go clean our sheets.

04:42.625 --> 04:44.625
And also this baby’s diaper

04:44.625 --> 04:48.333
because didn’t catch that
on the surveillance.

04:48.333 --> 04:49.625
I thought you said
you were gonna do that.

04:49.625 --> 04:51.083
Well, I’ll do it
if it’s our baby.

04:51.083 --> 04:52.208
Yeah.

04:52.208 --> 04:54.959
♪

04:54.959 --> 04:56.875
Oh, man. Look at this.

04:56.875 --> 04:59.667
Yeah, I get it,
Marmaduke’s a big boy.

04:59.667 --> 05:02.166
No. No. That virtual
health care company

05:02.166 --> 05:06.000
I wanted to invest in years ago
just went public.

05:06.000 --> 05:07.667
If you would have let me
invest that money

05:07.667 --> 05:09.667
my parents gave us,
we would be rich,

05:09.667 --> 05:11.875
and not in the stupid way
that you’re supposed to say

05:11.875 --> 05:13.959
with, like,
friends and health,

05:13.959 --> 05:16.125
but in the good way,
with money.

05:16.125 --> 05:17.250
Virtual health care?

05:17.250 --> 05:19.959
I never told you that
you couldn’t invest in that.

05:19.959 --> 05:22.000
Yes, you did!

05:22.000 --> 05:23.542
Babe, it was the biggest fight
we ever had.

05:23.542 --> 05:26.125
It caused my scalp
to reject my new hair plugs.

05:26.125 --> 05:28.417
Babe, biggest fight
we ever had

05:28.417 --> 05:31.083
was how much skill does it take
to become a game show host.

05:31.083 --> 05:32.542
It is very difficult,

05:32.542 --> 05:35.041
but I am talking about
a much bigger fight.

05:35.041 --> 05:36.709
We were screaming at each other

05:36.709 --> 05:38.792
in the middle of that
Asian fusion restaurant.

05:38.792 --> 05:39.959
You left crying.

05:39.959 --> 05:41.667
And then the delivery guy
had to drive me home

05:41.667 --> 05:42.709
on his handlebars.

05:42.709 --> 05:47.417
Oh, was that the place with
the hamburger egg rolls?

05:47.417 --> 05:48.875
So, you remember
the egg rolls,

05:48.875 --> 05:50.542
but you don’t remember
the biggest fight

05:50.542 --> 05:51.875
in the history
of our relationship?

05:51.875 --> 05:52.792
HEATHER: Oh, my God.

05:52.792 --> 05:55.291
I had a sex dream
about those egg rolls.

05:55.291 --> 05:56.792
♪

05:56.792 --> 05:57.792
TIM: All right, look,
I’m just upset

05:57.792 --> 06:00.500
because if your mom hadn’t
put the kibosh on my dreams,

06:00.500 --> 06:02.917
we’d all be wearing,
you know, name-brand sneakers

06:02.917 --> 06:04.709
instead of these Air Gordons.

06:04.709 --> 06:06.792
TYLER: Don’t you have to wear
those because of your corns?

06:06.792 --> 06:08.083
Look,
that’s not the point.

06:08.083 --> 06:09.792
The point is that
I want her to acknowledge

06:09.792 --> 06:11.709
how much money she cost us.

06:11.709 --> 06:13.625
You know, I mean, look,
this is the first time

06:13.625 --> 06:15.250
I’ve ever been proven right
in an argument,

06:15.250 --> 06:16.834
and now your mother
just conveniently

06:16.834 --> 06:17.750
forgets about it?

06:17.750 --> 06:19.166
TYLER: Dad, this space
is too small.

06:19.166 --> 06:20.542
Ah, I never
listen to people

06:20.542 --> 06:22.250
who say I can’t
fit into things.

06:22.250 --> 06:24.250
TYLER: Well, Clementine and I
like to handle

06:24.250 --> 06:25.875
our arguments
like mature adults.

06:25.875 --> 06:27.959
That’s why we only fight naked.
You should try it.

06:27.959 --> 06:28.875
CLEMENTINE:
Yeah, it helps remind you

06:28.875 --> 06:30.375
of each other’s vulnerabilities,

06:30.375 --> 06:32.125
and then the fights
don’t last as long.

06:32.125 --> 06:34.250
It’s called
Let Me Geni-Tell Ya.

06:34.250 --> 06:36.500
No, it’s not.
It’s called Nude Feud.

06:36.500 --> 06:38.291
Um, I think I know
what it’s called.

06:38.291 --> 06:39.834
My Mom and Uncle Dad
invented it.

06:39.834 --> 06:40.750
TYLER: No, they didn’t.

06:40.750 --> 06:42.542
I came up with it
when we got in that argument

06:42.542 --> 06:44.291
in the shower
about the pee rules.

06:44.291 --> 06:45.291
No, you didn’t.
Okay,

06:45.291 --> 06:46.750
we are settling this
right now.

06:46.750 --> 06:48.166
Hey, hey, hey, hey.

06:48.166 --> 06:50.458
Nobody’s getting naked
in my car unless it’s me.

06:50.458 --> 06:52.542
TYLER: Why should we take advice
from you and Mom?

06:52.542 --> 06:55.417
Do you know how traumatizing
it is to be a little kid

06:55.417 --> 06:57.250
and go into
an Asian Fusion restaurant,

06:57.250 --> 06:59.291
asking for your dad’s
hair plugs back?

06:59.291 --> 07:01.583
That was genuine
Norwegian corpse hair.

07:01.583 --> 07:03.750
I could have replanted
that stuff.

07:03.750 --> 07:04.959
And wait a minute.

07:04.959 --> 07:05.875
If you remember that,

07:05.875 --> 07:07.917
that means you remember
the argument.

07:07.917 --> 07:08.834
Oh!

07:08.834 --> 07:10.291
You got to tell your mom.

07:10.291 --> 07:12.083
Nobody’s getting ice cream
until you do.

07:12.083 --> 07:13.625
I didn’t even want ice cream.

07:13.625 --> 07:14.834
You asked us to come with you

07:14.834 --> 07:17.000
because you were
too embarrassed to go alone.

07:17.000 --> 07:19.000
That’s because I was
here this morning.

07:19.000 --> 07:20.041
All right, let’s go.

07:20.041 --> 07:22.583
And for the record,
I fit in the spot.

07:22.583 --> 07:24.792
TYLER: Yeah, I’d like
to see you pull out.

07:24.792 --> 07:26.792
♪

07:26.792 --> 07:28.333
I just want to make sure
that everyone has

07:28.333 --> 07:30.208
the same information,
so we can all agree

07:30.208 --> 07:31.625
that for once, I was right.

07:31.625 --> 07:32.750
Go ahead, Tyler.

07:32.750 --> 07:34.250
TYLER: So you and Dad came home,

07:34.250 --> 07:35.500
and you were arguing
about the investment.

07:35.500 --> 07:36.583
A-ha, yes!

07:36.583 --> 07:38.792
See? Now you remember.

07:38.792 --> 07:40.667
TYLER: Yeah, and then you said
that you make the money,

07:40.667 --> 07:42.208
so you get to make
the decisions.

07:42.208 --> 07:44.750
Oh, oh, whoa,
whoa, whoa, whoa.

07:44.750 --> 07:46.250
That sounds familiar.

07:46.250 --> 07:47.834
-I said that?
-Yeah.

07:47.834 --> 07:49.500
And then you said
that Mom got to decide

07:49.500 --> 07:50.750
what she packed for my lunch,

07:50.750 --> 07:52.458
and that was enough
decision-making for her, so...

07:52.458 --> 07:54.125
All right,
that’ll do, Tyler.

07:54.125 --> 07:56.500
Yeah, this is all
coming back to me now.

07:56.500 --> 07:57.667
But I didn’t even get
to the part

07:57.667 --> 07:59.583
-where you called her...
-Hey, who asked you, anyway?

07:59.583 --> 08:00.458
Right?

08:00.458 --> 08:03.125
I’m gonna go get you
a diamond bracelet

08:03.125 --> 08:04.959
out of my apology drawer.

08:04.959 --> 08:06.375
Wait, so,

08:06.375 --> 08:07.750
now you don’t want
to talk about it,

08:07.750 --> 08:10.375
now that I actually
remember the fight?

08:10.375 --> 08:11.583
Well, there’s no need to.

08:11.583 --> 08:14.834
Everybody’s memories
are sufficiently refreshed,

08:14.834 --> 08:16.750
and apologies accepted.

08:16.750 --> 08:18.291
Hey, I bet we’re all starving.

08:18.291 --> 08:20.250
-What are you making for...
HEATHER: For what, Tim?

08:20.250 --> 08:24.041
What am I making for what?

08:24.041 --> 08:28.458
For reservations for yourself
for the spa for tomorrow.

08:28.458 --> 08:30.750
HEATHER: Oh, yeah.
That is happening.

08:30.750 --> 08:32.417
But let’s get back to this,
about how

08:32.417 --> 08:34.542
you went out of your way
to demean me

08:34.542 --> 08:37.500
as a wife, a mother,
and a woman.

08:37.500 --> 08:38.792
And hey,
just so you know, guy,

08:38.792 --> 08:40.458
we can talk about this
all night long,

08:40.458 --> 08:44.083
because tomorrow’s lunches
are already packed.

08:44.083 --> 08:46.166
You two are gonna
want to leave.

08:46.166 --> 08:48.959
Wait, so your mom
is not making dinner?

08:48.959 --> 08:50.834
Oh, no,
he’s getting naked.

08:50.834 --> 08:51.792
We got to go.

08:51.792 --> 08:52.875
CLEMENTINE: We should not
have suggested this

08:52.875 --> 08:54.542
to anyone over the age of 20.

08:54.542 --> 08:55.667
TYLER: Okay...

08:55.667 --> 08:57.041
If you’re gonna do that thing
that you talk to me

08:57.041 --> 08:59.208
with your belly button,
I’m not in the mood.

08:59.208 --> 09:00.250
If this is gonna be
a big fight,

09:00.250 --> 09:02.125
we have to do it naked,
apparently that helps.

09:02.125 --> 09:03.750
(laughs)

09:03.750 --> 09:04.750
Okay.

09:04.750 --> 09:07.792
You know what?
I can fight with you naked

09:07.792 --> 09:09.959
just as well as I can
with my clothes on.

09:09.959 --> 09:12.792
In fact, naked...

09:12.792 --> 09:14.000
I got a lot more ammo.

09:16.458 --> 09:17.625
Full Monty.

09:21.333 --> 09:22.792
TIM: Okay, this works.

09:22.792 --> 09:24.917
-Yeah.
-I feel more vulnerable.

09:24.917 --> 09:27.083
(exhales)

09:27.083 --> 09:28.417
It’s hard to...

09:28.417 --> 09:30.166
It’s hard...

09:30.166 --> 09:31.542
I don’t know if I’d say that.

09:31.542 --> 09:33.291
It’s getting there, though.

09:33.291 --> 09:35.709
Oh.

09:35.709 --> 09:36.834
Oh, what were you
talking about?

09:36.834 --> 09:38.834
HEATHER: I was saying
it’s hard to be mad at you.

09:38.834 --> 09:39.792
But it’s, yeah...

09:39.792 --> 09:41.625
Don’t make me laugh,
it bounces.

09:41.625 --> 09:44.542
♪

09:44.542 --> 09:45.834
That was good.

09:45.834 --> 09:48.125
That was really good.

09:48.125 --> 09:51.208
Hey, I’m sorry about
all the money that I lost us.

09:51.208 --> 09:54.125
Oh, it’s okay.

09:54.125 --> 09:55.625
I’m sorry, too,

09:55.625 --> 09:59.208
that I demeaned you
as a wife and a mother.

09:59.208 --> 10:01.125
(both laughing)

10:02.583 --> 10:04.375
I love it.
I don’t know why I said

10:04.375 --> 10:05.709
that I wasn’t in the mood.

10:05.709 --> 10:08.083
I’m always in the mood
for that.

10:08.083 --> 10:10.542
Mm.

10:10.542 --> 10:13.333
I wish you would have
proposed to me like that.

10:13.333 --> 10:14.959
♪

10:14.959 --> 10:16.333
GREG: I mean, how many
other kids you know

10:16.333 --> 10:19.041
that’s got a real professional
inventor in their family?

10:19.041 --> 10:21.417
Actually, Kyle Edison’s
great, great...

10:21.417 --> 10:22.834
Yeah, whatever.

10:24.917 --> 10:27.458
♪

10:27.458 --> 10:29.166
GREG:
Welcome to the Dream Lab.

10:29.166 --> 10:30.917
So tell me about your project.

10:30.917 --> 10:33.333
I have to come up with an idea,
build a prototype,

10:33.333 --> 10:35.083
and then develop
a business plan.

10:35.083 --> 10:36.125
It’s so stupid.

10:36.125 --> 10:37.500
If I actually had
any good ideas,

10:37.500 --> 10:40.041
then I would already be
an inventor.

10:40.041 --> 10:42.625
Well, it’s a good thing little
Ricky Hammock didn’t say that.

10:42.625 --> 10:44.250
Although he would have been
so much more productive

10:44.250 --> 10:47.625
if his first invention
wasn’t a hammock.

10:47.625 --> 10:48.667
(clears throat)

10:48.667 --> 10:50.583
Excuse me.

10:50.583 --> 10:52.709
I had those when I was little.

10:52.709 --> 10:54.291
And that’s precisely
the problem.

10:54.291 --> 10:55.709
See, it’s not just little kids

10:55.709 --> 10:57.208
that need to get to places
in a hurry.

10:57.208 --> 10:59.500
It’s also big, important people,
such as myself.

10:59.500 --> 11:01.542
Well, they do
make you look taller.

11:01.542 --> 11:03.542
I’d do anything for that.

11:03.542 --> 11:04.917
Why don’t you just wear heels?

11:04.917 --> 11:06.458
My mom won’t let me.

11:06.458 --> 11:08.875
If only they made shoes
with retractable heels,

11:08.875 --> 11:10.250
then I could leave
the house in flats,

11:10.250 --> 11:12.417
then switch to heels
when I got to school.

11:12.417 --> 11:13.542
Bingo.

11:13.542 --> 11:14.792
Sam, it’s brilliant.

11:14.792 --> 11:16.417
That’s your idea.

11:16.417 --> 11:19.041
We can call them
Swiss Army Heels.

11:19.041 --> 11:21.625
Or how about Peek-A-Boots?

11:21.625 --> 11:22.834
Eh.

11:22.834 --> 11:25.291
It’s good to have options.

11:25.291 --> 11:27.208
Oh!

11:27.208 --> 11:30.750
♪

11:30.750 --> 11:32.208
Huh.

11:32.208 --> 11:34.375
SAMANTHA: So, what do you think?

11:34.375 --> 11:36.917
Well, I think
it’s a good draft.

11:36.917 --> 11:39.125
But--just playing
devil’s advocate here--

11:39.125 --> 11:42.750
I was just envisioning
this totally different,

11:42.750 --> 11:44.959
and just a little bit better.

11:44.959 --> 11:46.166
Uh...

11:46.166 --> 11:48.166
So lose that.

11:48.166 --> 11:49.709
Keep this first word,

11:49.709 --> 11:51.583
but then all of that’s
got to go.

11:51.583 --> 11:53.458
Uh, you know what?

11:53.458 --> 11:55.333
What do you say
we just start from scratch?

11:55.333 --> 11:56.917
Shall we?

11:56.917 --> 11:58.417
So, let’s...

11:58.417 --> 11:59.834
What if we make
the straps...

11:59.834 --> 12:01.000
Uh, shh, shh.

12:01.000 --> 12:02.583
-Okay, um...
-All right?

12:02.583 --> 12:05.375
My ideas are whispering to me,
and I have to...

12:05.375 --> 12:07.917
♪

12:07.917 --> 12:09.041
(door closes)

12:09.041 --> 12:10.959
GREG: Hey!
HEATHER: Hey.

12:10.959 --> 12:13.166
Look who stopped over to see
how you did on your project.

12:13.166 --> 12:14.542
So, how’d we do?

12:14.542 --> 12:16.250
I got a B+.

12:16.250 --> 12:18.458
-B+.
-That’s so great!

12:18.458 --> 12:19.917
Thank you, little brother.

12:19.917 --> 12:21.083
Thanks for what?

12:21.083 --> 12:22.291
I invented a failure.

12:22.291 --> 12:23.208
Oh, God.

12:23.208 --> 12:25.000
No, I am
a professional inventor,

12:25.000 --> 12:27.166
I should be getting an A-
at least.

12:27.166 --> 12:28.458
Minimum.

12:28.458 --> 12:31.291
I got to get to my Dream Lab.

12:31.291 --> 12:32.375
MRS. SANDOVAL:
What made da Vinci

12:32.375 --> 12:36.709
so influential to Tesla
was his...

12:36.709 --> 12:38.625
GREG: Hello.
Uh, my name is Greg Short,

12:38.625 --> 12:39.834
and I have a problem.

12:39.834 --> 12:42.875
Sir, the A.A. meeting
isn’t until 6:00.

12:42.875 --> 12:43.875
GREG: No. No, no, no.

12:43.875 --> 12:46.375
I am, uh, Sam’s uncle, here.

12:46.375 --> 12:49.875
And I’d like to speak with you
about her grade.

12:49.875 --> 12:51.667
-I’m teaching.
-Are you?

12:51.667 --> 12:52.709
Because it really sounds

12:52.709 --> 12:54.375
like you’re
unfairly criticizing.

12:54.375 --> 12:56.959
Samantha’s prototype
was amazing,

12:56.959 --> 13:00.458
and her essay was
super, duper smart,

13:00.458 --> 13:02.959
I mean, it included
very witty wordplay,

13:02.959 --> 13:05.917
such as, uh,
"Come heel or high water."

13:05.917 --> 13:08.000
Sir, did you do
her project for her?

13:08.000 --> 13:09.834
No. No, I did not.

13:09.834 --> 13:13.166
But I am a professional,
um, inventor,

13:13.166 --> 13:15.750
and I know a good idea
when I hear one.

13:15.750 --> 13:18.208
MRS. SANDOVAL: Oh.
We’ve been studying inventors.

13:18.208 --> 13:21.625
Maybe you could tell the class
about your work.

13:21.625 --> 13:23.333
Oh. Uh...

13:23.333 --> 13:25.542
All right, sure.
Yeah, I can spit my flow.

13:25.542 --> 13:26.667
SAMANTHA: Mrs. Sandoval,

13:26.667 --> 13:28.667
can I take a mental health day?

13:28.667 --> 13:30.792
GREG: So, as I’m sure
Sam told you,

13:30.792 --> 13:33.375
I’m the guy
that invented CryTunes.

13:33.375 --> 13:35.709
Ha.

13:35.709 --> 13:39.750
Which is a monitor
that, uh, converts the sound

13:39.750 --> 13:43.500
of a crying baby
into smooth jazz.

13:43.500 --> 13:45.333
It’s something
my wife and I have been using

13:45.333 --> 13:46.417
with our daughter.

13:46.417 --> 13:47.709
STUDENT: Wife?

13:47.709 --> 13:49.417
Yeah, I have a wife.

13:49.417 --> 13:50.709
Do you have any more questions?

13:50.709 --> 13:52.583
STUDENT: Do you always ignore
your child

13:52.583 --> 13:53.709
when it’s in distress?

13:53.709 --> 13:55.417
GREG: Uh, it’s not ignoring.

13:55.417 --> 13:57.083
STUDENT: So if a stranger
abducts your baby,

13:57.083 --> 13:58.625
you’d just hear jazz?

13:58.625 --> 14:00.750
STUDENT: Yeah, this idea
is completely unsafe.

14:00.750 --> 14:03.125
-No, it’s not.
-Good comeback.

14:03.125 --> 14:05.125
MRS. SANDOVAL: Why don’t you
talk more about how you plan

14:05.125 --> 14:07.000
on growing your business?

14:07.000 --> 14:08.875
Yeah. Yeah.

14:08.875 --> 14:13.083
We are growing at, uh,
an almost-alarming rate.

14:13.083 --> 14:14.542
But in a good way.

14:14.542 --> 14:17.667
Uh, we’re trying to expand
our musical libraries

14:17.667 --> 14:20.709
to include alt-rock, alt-ska.

14:20.709 --> 14:21.917
All the alts.

14:21.917 --> 14:23.709
STUDENT: Do you have
the licensing for that?

14:23.709 --> 14:25.208
Uh, not yet.

14:25.208 --> 14:27.792
STUDENT: This is
a legal nightmare.

14:27.792 --> 14:29.458
Okay, look,
I’m talking with people

14:29.458 --> 14:32.291
about selling my company
for a lot of money, so...

14:32.291 --> 14:35.125
STUDENT: Then why
are you talking to us?

14:35.125 --> 14:36.875
Because I love the children.

14:36.875 --> 14:38.333
♪

14:38.333 --> 14:39.750
I hate them.

14:39.750 --> 14:41.083
They ridiculed me.

14:41.083 --> 14:43.417
First it was CryTunes,
then it was my jeans,

14:43.417 --> 14:44.542
then it was my posture.

14:44.542 --> 14:45.917
JEN: Aw, honey.

14:45.917 --> 14:47.333
They didn’t mention you wearing
your sunglasses

14:47.333 --> 14:48.458
on the back of your neck.

14:48.458 --> 14:49.583
(knocking)

14:49.583 --> 14:50.667
Who’s that?

14:50.667 --> 14:52.250
Sam? Hi.

14:52.250 --> 14:53.500
What are you doing here?

14:53.500 --> 14:55.542
Have you come to make fun
of my phone case, too?

14:55.542 --> 14:56.875
They made fun of my phone case.

14:56.875 --> 14:59.083
I’m really sorry
about all that.

14:59.083 --> 15:00.709
If it makes you feel any better,

15:00.709 --> 15:03.208
one of the boys
thought you were cute.

15:03.208 --> 15:04.542
Eh, you’re just saying that.

15:04.542 --> 15:05.709
SAMANTHA: Okay, I am.

15:05.709 --> 15:06.917
But for real.

15:06.917 --> 15:09.125
One of my friend’s parents
invests in startups,

15:09.125 --> 15:11.291
and he loves Peek-A-Boots.

15:11.291 --> 15:12.625
He wants to fund it.

15:12.625 --> 15:15.625
What? That’s amazing.

15:15.625 --> 15:18.667
Yeah. That’s--that’s
really great news,

15:18.667 --> 15:21.250
that there’s a successful
inventor in the family.

15:21.250 --> 15:22.667
I’m very happy for you.

15:22.667 --> 15:24.208
What do you mean "me"?

15:24.208 --> 15:25.792
This is our idea.

15:25.792 --> 15:28.291
I can’t do this
without you.

15:28.291 --> 15:29.917
Really?

15:29.917 --> 15:31.083
Okay.

15:31.083 --> 15:32.083
Uh...

15:32.083 --> 15:33.417
I like the sound of this.

15:33.417 --> 15:34.542
Me, too.

15:34.542 --> 15:36.667
Partners. 70/30.

15:36.667 --> 15:38.250
JEN: Okay, well, that’s not
contractually binding.

15:38.250 --> 15:39.375
I’ll write something up.

15:39.375 --> 15:40.917
Let’s go celebrate, right?

15:40.917 --> 15:42.500
This is so exciting, you guys.

15:45.000 --> 15:47.417
GREG: Be right back.

15:47.417 --> 15:50.166
(whistling)

15:50.166 --> 15:51.750
♪

15:51.750 --> 15:53.417
JOHN: I don’t touch bugs,
you know?

15:53.417 --> 15:54.458
They’re icky.

15:54.458 --> 15:56.375
Didn’t you fight in a war?

15:56.375 --> 15:58.834
Some say I still am.

16:01.417 --> 16:05.125
♪

16:05.125 --> 16:06.166
JOAN: Hi, sweetie.

16:06.166 --> 16:07.709
JOHN: Hey, there’s
our favorite

16:07.709 --> 16:11.250
almost eight or nine-year-old
granddaughter.

16:11.250 --> 16:13.333
JOAN: We got you
an early birthday gift

16:13.333 --> 16:15.500
because we couldn’t wait
to shower you with love

16:15.500 --> 16:17.667
and my coupon expires tomorrow.

16:17.667 --> 16:19.417
Oh, you shouldn’t have, guys.

16:19.417 --> 16:21.667
Because this year
I just want gift cards.

16:21.667 --> 16:23.291
That way,
I can get what I want,

16:23.291 --> 16:25.375
and not just a bunch
of pink stuff.

16:25.375 --> 16:27.500
Giving gifts is not
about buying someone

16:27.500 --> 16:29.250
something they want,
it’s about getting them

16:29.250 --> 16:30.625
something they don’t want,

16:30.625 --> 16:33.250
so they learn
to appreciate it.

16:33.250 --> 16:35.750
-You want to open it?
-Yes. Thank you.

16:42.333 --> 16:43.750
A butterfly kit?

16:43.750 --> 16:47.333
JOAN: Yes!
Those little squirmy wormies

16:47.333 --> 16:50.959
are gonna transform magically
into butterflies.

16:50.959 --> 16:52.959
They are
nature’s drag queens.

16:52.959 --> 16:55.000
SOPHIA: Thanks.
How long does it take?

16:55.000 --> 16:56.417
Mm, just two weeks.

16:56.417 --> 16:58.083
-Two weeks?
-Yeah.

16:58.083 --> 17:00.250
Couldn’t you have thrown down
a few extra bucks

17:00.250 --> 17:02.583
to get the same-day butterflies?

17:02.583 --> 17:05.208
I mean, you got a pension,
right, Pop-Pop?

17:05.208 --> 17:06.667
JOHN: Look,
you can’t pay nature

17:06.667 --> 17:07.875
to hurry things along.

17:07.875 --> 17:11.125
If you could, I wouldn’t clock
so many hours on the toilet.

17:11.125 --> 17:12.500
-Ha.
-Ugh.

17:12.500 --> 17:15.375
♪

17:15.375 --> 17:18.792
SOPHIA: Wow, these cocoons
are even more boring

17:18.792 --> 17:21.166
than the movie
of the same name.

17:21.166 --> 17:22.709
JOHN: Boring?

17:22.709 --> 17:24.083
Inside the cocoon,

17:24.083 --> 17:26.291
the caterpillar
is digesting itself.

17:26.291 --> 17:28.166
If you were to cut it open,

17:28.166 --> 17:30.625
caterpillar guts
would ooze out.

17:30.625 --> 17:31.667
Ooh, let’s do that.

17:31.667 --> 17:33.083
JOHN: Oh, no! Wait, wait. No.

17:33.083 --> 17:34.917
This is the exciting part,

17:34.917 --> 17:36.959
where you get to watch them

17:36.959 --> 17:40.166
hang there for,
like, ten more days.

17:40.166 --> 17:41.834
(groans)

17:41.834 --> 17:42.834
Fine.

17:42.834 --> 17:44.333
Great idea.

17:44.333 --> 17:46.792
You’re gonna want
to remember this experience.

17:46.792 --> 17:50.792
Actually, Michelangelo in class
said that he would buy these.

17:50.792 --> 17:52.500
And since I really
ripped him off

17:52.500 --> 17:55.834
in our last business venture,
he wants pictures first.

17:55.834 --> 17:57.458
So you’re selling them, hm?

17:57.458 --> 17:58.959
-Mm-hm.
-Okay, then.

17:58.959 --> 18:02.667
Uh, well, I’m sure Micacacalo
will give them a good home.

18:02.667 --> 18:04.792
A good mobile home.

18:04.792 --> 18:07.250
♪

18:07.250 --> 18:09.375
Sophia wants
to sell our butterflies

18:09.375 --> 18:13.291
because she says,
"They’re boring."

18:13.291 --> 18:15.041
Oh, why are kids so impatient?

18:15.041 --> 18:16.959
She needs to grow up already.

18:16.959 --> 18:18.500
Well, it seems to me

18:18.500 --> 18:21.208
some older folks
can be impatient, too.

18:21.208 --> 18:23.250
I don’t have time for this.

18:23.250 --> 18:26.208
Why is everybody so annoying?

18:26.208 --> 18:29.875
♪

18:29.875 --> 18:31.834
Sophia.

18:31.834 --> 18:34.625
Look, I understand
if you want to sell

18:34.625 --> 18:37.458
a piece of Pop-Pop’s heart.

18:37.458 --> 18:38.750
I mean, butterflies.

18:38.750 --> 18:40.375
SOPHIA: Pop-Pop,
one of the cocoons

18:40.375 --> 18:42.000
fell off the branch.

18:42.000 --> 18:43.500
I don’t want him to die.

18:43.500 --> 18:44.500
I’m only nine,

18:44.500 --> 18:46.500
and I’ve already buried
three pets

18:46.500 --> 18:49.208
and my sheets that...

18:49.208 --> 18:51.333
someone peed on.

18:51.333 --> 18:54.041
Well, I’ll try to reattach him
to the branch.

18:54.041 --> 18:55.041
But I’ll warn you,

18:55.041 --> 18:56.667
it’s gonna be a risky procedure,

18:56.667 --> 18:59.000
because I don’t touch bugs.

18:59.000 --> 19:00.583
They’re icky.

19:00.583 --> 19:03.125
♪

19:03.125 --> 19:06.250
I do this for Dad
when he’s making a sandwich.

19:06.250 --> 19:08.291
Ah, well.

19:08.291 --> 19:11.792
Yeah, we’ve done all we can
to save one of God’s creatures.

19:11.792 --> 19:13.792
I’m gonna name her Deirdre.

19:13.792 --> 19:14.709
Well, I guess that’s fair,

19:14.709 --> 19:17.500
since I named all
of those other ones John.

19:17.500 --> 19:20.667
I really hope
she pulls through.

19:20.667 --> 19:23.667
Or dies quickly,
so she’s not a burden.

19:26.125 --> 19:27.500
♪

19:27.500 --> 19:28.917
Did I miss it?

19:28.917 --> 19:31.625
I ran out on my probation
hearing at the country club

19:31.625 --> 19:32.625
as soon as I heard.

19:32.625 --> 19:34.083
SOPHIA: Nope,
you’re just in time.

19:34.083 --> 19:35.041
They’re hatching.

19:35.041 --> 19:36.375
Ooh, thank God.

19:36.375 --> 19:38.083
It’s the only hobby
I got left.

19:39.667 --> 19:42.375
Oh, no, Deirdre never came out.

19:42.375 --> 19:44.667
But let’s not tell
the other butterflies yet.

19:44.667 --> 19:47.375
Let them keep their innocence
a little longer.

19:47.375 --> 19:49.709
Sweetie, I’m sure
she’s flying in heaven.

19:49.709 --> 19:51.166
Yeah, but everyone
flies up there,

19:51.166 --> 19:53.834
so it’s, like, no big deal.

19:53.834 --> 19:55.792
No, look, she’s hatching!

19:55.792 --> 20:02.709
♪

20:05.875 --> 20:08.625
Why is saying goodbye
always so hard?

20:08.625 --> 20:10.333
I know,
but if you love something,

20:10.333 --> 20:11.959
you have to set it free, right?

20:11.959 --> 20:14.500
Is that’s why you walk
around with your robe open?

20:14.500 --> 20:16.875
SOPHIA:
This is the best gift ever.

20:16.875 --> 20:19.291
When I grow up, I’m gonna get
a butterfly tattoo

20:19.291 --> 20:20.792
on my lower back.

20:20.792 --> 20:22.208
You want to do the honors?

20:22.208 --> 20:24.709
(exhales)

20:24.709 --> 20:28.000
♪

20:28.000 --> 20:30.500
(laughter)

20:30.500 --> 20:36.458
♪

20:36.458 --> 20:38.750
(squawking)

20:38.750 --> 20:41.000
(gasping)

20:42.500 --> 20:45.041
What are those crows doing?

20:45.041 --> 20:46.500
They’re just
saying hello.

20:46.500 --> 20:49.166
Uh, you know, welcoming them
to the neighborhood.

20:49.166 --> 20:50.166
SOPHIA:
Oh, that was nice of them.

20:50.166 --> 20:52.375
-They’re happy they’re here.
-Yeah, well, if the lesson

20:52.375 --> 20:53.500
about life wasn’t quick,

20:53.500 --> 20:55.291
the one about death
sure is, huh?

20:55.291 --> 20:56.125
SOPHIA: What do you mean?

20:57.041 --> 21:03.959
♪
